Berkeley Crime Data¶

Let's take a look at some crime data from Berkeley, Ca! I started this notebook for some basic data exploration and to gain some experience with GeoPandas. That evolved into trying to see if I could use a Random Forest Classifier to predict crimes in Berkeley. Throughout this notebook I'll provide some interesting insights into where certain crimes occur in Berkeley and places to be extra cautious when parking your car.

The data used in this analysis comes from https://data.cityofberkeley.info/browse, which has a variety publicly available data for Berkeley (including where trees major trees are located in the city). I highly recommend checking it out if you're looking for some data to work on.

To run this notebook you'll need Berkeley block group maps (downloaded as shapefiles) and the most recent Berkeley-PD calls for services as a csv.

In [2]:
crime_data = pd.read_csv('Berkeley_PD_-_Calls_for_Service.csv')

def get_point(loc_str):
    try:
        lat, lng = map(float, loc_str.split('\n')[-1][1:-2].split(','))
        return Point(lng, lat)
    except ValueError:
        return Point([-1,-1])

crime_data.rename(columns={'CASENO':'Case Number', 
                           'OFFENSE': 'Offense', 
                           'EVENTDT': 'Event Date',
                           'EVENTTM': 'Event Time',
                           'CVLEGEND': 'Crime Legend',
                           'CVDOW':'Day of Week',
                           'InDbDate':'Database Date',
                           'Block_Location': 'Location',
                           'BLKADDR': 'Block Address'}, inplace=True)

crime_data['Coord'] = crime_data['Location'].map(get_point)
crime_data = crime_data.drop('Location', axis=1)

Now that we have shown some general trends in time for when car burglaries occur, let's now try to figure out where these actually take place.

Where are car burglaries more likely to happen in Berkeley?¶

Let's now plot these car burglaries on the map of Berkeley. To do this we use Geopandas. First we've instantiated a GeoDataFrame with the crime_data panadas DataFram from above. We need to tell the GeoDataFrame which column contains the Geo data (geometry). This is why we created the Point geometries for the crimes using their lat and long.

We can also read in the shapefiles that have the polygons describing the boundaries of block groups.

One last note: Every GeoDataFrame needs to have a Coordinate Reference System (crs) set. There are thousands of these but the moset comonly used one is epsg:4326.

This just shows the boundaries of Berkeley neighborhoods and all of the burglaries as red dots. Let's take a look and see what neighborhoods have the most car burgularies by looking at the burglary per area. If you look at just the number of burgularies in a given neighborhood, we get skewed toward larger neighborhoods (i.e. down by Berkeley marina on the left side of the plot).

To do this, we join the geo_crime_data and Berkeley tables with a left join and then count the number of incidents. Then do a dataframe merge with the Berkeley dataframe (which joins on blkgrpce10). We then create a new column of crime_density and plot using the handy geopandas plot function!

Can we predict crimes?¶

Now that we have some familiarity with the data, let's put this data to good use and try to predict crimes. Specifically, the question I want to ask is, "can I predict what type of crime is going to occur given the date, time, and location of the crime?" This is a classic classification prediction problem.

Berkeley only offers data for the past 6 months, and I initially downloaded data back in October, but recently downloaded a newer data set that doesn't overlap. This gives us roughly a year of data.

Making Features¶

Let's organize our data and make some features. There's a number of data reductions we need to do.

  1. First we need to build up our classes. We'll categorize the 'Crime Legend' column and will be our targets for our classification algorithm. Looking at the data below, I noticed that there were some categories which only had a handful of reports and thus the distribution into the training, validation, and test set are hard to get evenly. We'll remove those low number crimes (< 10) to get a better distribution. This has the draw back of never being able to classify those crimes with future data.
  2. Next, we need to figure out what are the features we are going to use. I'll build a model using the data we have. Specifically, we'll use location data (lat, long), the day of the week, and the date and time of the crime. I'll additionally engineer some features from this indicating if the date is a weekend or a weekday.
  3. Finally, we need to decide what type of classifier we are going to use. For this exercise, I'll use logistic regression as the base model and then use a random forest classifier to see if we can do better.
In [12]:
# remove crime types that are fewer than 10 in number.
new_crime_data = new_crime_data.groupby('Crime Legend').filter(lambda x: x['City'].count() > 10, dropna=True)
new_crime_data = new_crime_data.reset_index(drop=True)

# get classes of crimes from Crime Legend
classes = list(new_crime_data['Crime Legend'].unique())

# create an empty data frame for features
feature_df = pd.DataFrame()

# getting the date and time of each crime
d = new_crime_data['Event Date'].map(lambda x: x.split(' ')[0])
t = new_crime_data['Event Time']

feature_df['dtime'] = pd.to_datetime(d, format='%m/%d/%Y')
feature_df['time'] = pd.to_datetime(t)
# fix time in datetime object and drop time column
feature_df['dtime'] = feature_df.apply(lambda x: x.dtime.replace(hour=x.time.hour, minute=x.time.minute), axis=1)
feature_df.drop('time', axis=1, inplace=True)

# add in coordinates
feature_df['long'] = new_crime_data['Coord'].apply(lambda x: x.coords[0][0])
feature_df['lat'] = new_crime_data['Coord'].apply(lambda x: x.coords[0][1])

# drop rows with bad location data. These have lat,long = -1.0
drop_indexes = np.where(feature_df['long'] == -1.0)[0]
feature_df = feature_df.drop(drop_indexes)

# label the crimes 
feature_df['labels'] = new_crime_data['Crime Legend'].apply(lambda x: classes.index(x))

feature_df['hour'] = feature_df.dtime.map(lambda x: x.hour)

I have split the data set (~10000 samples) into a training set (60% of data), validation set (20% of data), and test set (20% of data). Now it's time to train up some models using the test set. I start with logistic regression.

Logistic Regression¶

We'll start off by using logistic regression. Logistic regression is the standard classification algorithm that is often use as the base model that all other models are compared too. We will take this route here and look at how well we are doing.

In [16]:
clf_logit = LogisticRegression()
clf_logit.fit(X_train, Y_train);
print("Logistic Regression has accuracy {0}".format(np.mean(clf_logit.predict(X_val) == Y_val)))

Logistic Regression has accuracy 0.224563206578

Now we can tune some logistic regression parameters to tweak this model to work best on the validation set. We'll tune the regularization scalar and the type of regularization (either L1 or L2).

In [17]:
Cs = [.01, .03, .1, .3, 1., 10] # create list of inverse regularization strengths
logit_models = {}
for _C in Cs:
    for norm in ['l1', 'l2']:
        clf_logit = LogisticRegression(C=_C, penalty=norm)
        clf_logit.fit(X_train, Y_train);
        logit_models[norm,_C] = clf_logit
        print("Logistic Regression with {0} norm and C={1} has accuracy={2}, log loss={3} ".format(norm, _C, np.mean(clf_logit.predict(X_val) == Y_val), log_loss(Y_val, clf_logit.predict_proba(X_val))))

So we've established our base model and we're getting around ~23% accuracy on the validation set and the log loss bottoms out at 2.5. This is also with essentially the defaults out of scikit-learn. Let's keep this in mind as our base accuracy and log loss.

Let's try another model now. I'll use a RandomForest classifier to classify the data. Since we have features that are on different scales (for example binary features and the coordinates of the crime) and since we haven't done any feature normalization, RF is the best bet for a better multiclass classification algorithm. It is also less suceptable to over fitting since it uses ensemble methods.

Random Forest¶

Let's see if we can do better with a random forest classifier. I'm using scikit-learns defaults for RandomForest with 4 trees in the forest as my base. We'll then optimze and tune parameters. I am choosing to optimize 2 parameters, the number of trees in a forest and the minimum sample for leafs. The minimum leaf size is the number of samples that end a tree.

In [18]:
clf_rf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=4)
clf_rf.fit(X_train, Y_train);
print("Random Forest has accuracy={0}, log loss={1} ".format(np.mean(clf_rf.predict(X_val) == Y_val), log_loss(Y_val, clf_rf.predict_proba(X_val))))

# optimizing 
n_estimators = [4, 20, 50, 100, 500, 1000]
min_sample_leafs = [1, 10, 50, 100]
models = {}
for n_estimator in n_estimators:
    for msl in min_sample_leafs:
        _clf_rf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=n_estimator, min_samples_leaf=msl)
        _clf_rf.fit(X_train, Y_train)
        models[(n_estimator, msl)] = _clf_rf 
        print("Random Forest with {0} estimators and msl={1} has accuracy={2}, log loss={3} ".format(n_estimator, msl, np.mean(_clf_rf.predict(X_val) == Y_val), log_loss(Y_val, _clf_rf.predict_proba(X_val))))

For our default RF model, we are seeing an accuracy gain of about 5%. This is an improvement over logistic regression. In our small parameter space search we are seeing that both n_estimators and minimum leaf size have an effect on the final accuracy and loss. A more thorough paramter space search would be needed to see if other parameters effect the final outcome more than n_estimators. In the best case scenario, we are getting 28.4% accuracy with a RF with 1000 estimators and a min_sample_leaf=10.

Now that we have our two models, logistic regression (of which I use the default one) and our best RF model, let's see how it performs on the Test set.

base_logit = logit_models['l1', .03]

The Confusion Matrix¶

The confusion matrix can be an informative plot for a classification algorithms. It shows the false positives and negatives that are classified by the classifier.

From the confusion matrix we see that the logistic regression classifier is only predicting data as a vehicle burglary or a larceny, the two most dominant reported crimes. Logistic regression does not have enough flexibility to determine the complex classification space. On the other hand, random forest does slightly better, but it is still classifying reports based on the most reported crimes. At least, it didn't turn into a binary classifier.

Summary¶

To summarize, I have explored crime data from the Berekely Data website. Using Geopandas I was able to show where in Berkeley the highest density of car thefts are and then took a look at if I could predict crimes using the data set. Using the data at hand, I used feature engineering to take the simple timestamp and coordinate of the crime to create meaningful features like what month, day of the week, and hour the crime took place. Training both a simple logistic regression and random forest model, I found that the random forest model is around 29% accurate on determining what type of crime is going to occur given the time and place of the event.

It is clear that more data is needed in order to build a better model of crime classification in Berkeley. Specifically, more diverse data is probably required such as specifics from the crime report (what was stolen, where was it, how loud, etc...). Then using natural language processing, there is potential to refine models.

Additionally, we can use the data in a different way. Instead of trying to predict the type of crime, we could try to answer a more practical question. This question would be to make build a model such that given a time, a location, and other tbd features, the probability that your car would be broken into. This question is a little more practical in the sense that there is a useful deliverable.

However, the types of models built here highlight that certain areas are prone to crime and help police departments distribute resources given the time of day and location.It can help provide information to where certain types of crime are occuring and can provoke cities to implement campaigns (such as surveilence videos) in certain areas to deter crimes.

I hope that this notebook helps you get started on your data adventures!
